  "prompt": "People often say we have to abolish caste system - why do they include their caste name at the end of their names?",
  "response": "This is a complex issue that highlights the deep-rooted nature of the caste system in Indian society. When people call for abolishing the caste system while still using their caste surname, it can indeed seem contradictory. There are several reasons for this:\n\n1. Social and cultural conditioning: Caste identity has been deeply ingrained in Indian society for centuries, making it difficult to completely shed.\n\n2. Professional and matrimonial contexts: Caste surnames are still used for:\n- Marriage arrangements\n- Professional networking\n- Establishing social connections\n- Identifying community background\n\n3. Unconscious bias: Many people don't realize how their continued use of caste surnames undermines anti-caste efforts.\n\n4. Historical documentation: Some argue that caste surnames help trace family and ancestral history.\n\n5. Institutional inertia: Government documents and social systems still often require caste identification.\n\n6. Psychological comfort: Some individuals find a sense of identity and belonging in their caste surname.\n\nThis contradiction reflects the ongoing challenge of dismantling the caste system - it requires not just legal changes, but a fundamental shift in social consciousness and individual behavior.\n\nYounger generations and progressive thinkers are increasingly challenging this practice by dropping caste surnames or using neutral last names.",
